==Marriage and descendants==
On 12 September 1309,{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} Afonso married [[Beatrice of Castile (1293–1359)|Beatrice of Castile]], daughter of [[Sancho IV of Castile]], and [[María de Molina]],{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=312}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=215}} and had four sons and three daughters. Afonso broke the tradition of previous kings and did not have any children out of wedlock.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|"We assume that after the marriage of dona Beatriz and don Alfonso IV, married life was harmonious (...) based on the fact that D. Afonso IV did not have any bastard children, thereby breaking a long family tradition" (loose translation){{Sfn|Lourenço Menino|2008|p=356}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|"Perhaps since he had so many problems with those of his father, D. Afonso did not have any illegitimate children." (loose translation){{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}}}{{refn|group=lower-alpha|"There are no known bastard children of the king. Two possible explanations could be the ties of profound esteem, friendship and respect that existed because he had been raised and had lived from a very early age with his future wife or, perhaps, because he wanted to avoid that his heirs had the same problems that he had had with his bastard brothers".(loose translation){{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}}}

* [[Maria of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Maria]] (1313{{snd}}18 January 1357),{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|pp=317 y 322}}{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} was the wife of [[Alfonso XI of Castile]],{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} and mother of the future king [[Peter I of Castile]]. Due to the affair of her husband with his mistress [[Leonor de Guzmán]] "it was an unfortunate union from the start, contributing to dampening the relations of both kingdoms";{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=218}} 
* Afonso (1315–1317), heir to the throne, died in his infancy.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} Buried at the disappeared Convento das Donas of the Dominican Order in Santarém;{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  
* Denis (born 12 February 1317), heir to the throne, died a few months after his birth,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} and was buried in [[Alcobaça Monastery]];{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}} 
* [[Peter I of Portugal|Peter]] (8 April 1320{{snd}}18 January 1367), the first surviving male offspring, he succeeded his father.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} {{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}} When his wife [[Constance of Peñafiel|Constance]] died in 1345, Queen Beatrice took care of the education of the two orphans, the ''infantes'' [[Maria, Marchioness of Tortosa|Maria]] and Ferdinand, who later reigned as King [[Ferdinand I of Portugal]];{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=228-229}}
* Isabel (21 December 1324{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}}{{snd}}11 July 1326), buried at the [[Monastery of Santa Clara-a-Velha]] in [[Coimbra]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}{{Sfn|Sousa|1735|p=315}}  
* John (23 September 1326{{snd}}21 June 1327), buried at the [[Monastery of São Dinis de Odivelas]];{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}
* [[Eleanor of Portugal, Queen of Aragon|Eleanor]] (1328–1348), born in the same year as her sister Maria's wedding,{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|p=217}} she married King [[Peter IV of Aragon]] in November 1347 and died a year after her marriage succumbing to the Black Death.{{Sfn|Rodrigues Oliveira|2010|pp=217, 220}}{{Sfn|Sotto Mayor Pizarro|1997|p=201}}

